Whereas African-Americans are diagnosed with AIDS later
			 than their nonminority counterparts, are confronted with barriers in accessing
			 care and treatment, and face higher morbidity and mortality outcomes;

Whereas approximately 619,400 people have died of AIDS in
			 the United States from the beginning of the HIV/AIDS epidemic through 2012, and
			 African-Americans account for approximately 40 percent of such deaths;

Whereas life-saving treatment is also proven prevention,
			 and research shows that antiretroviral drugs can reduce the risk of
			 transmitting HIV/AIDS by up to 96 percent;

